post_text: Happy Fryday! üçü That is no typo. Ms. Brown from Mountain View School donned a fun cardboard French Fry costume to get her first grade Kiddos excited for the weekend and the return to in person classes on Monday, September 14. Ms. Brown took the extra time to make sure all her students said goodbye to one another in the virtual classroom. During remote learning, Ms. Brown made sure that the kids felt like they were all one class even though some of them will still be learning from home. The first grade students really got to know each other even in this virtual world. She is truly a wonderful caring teacher. She has handled this new way of teaching with such grace. She is always telling parents that they are doing great and not to sweat the small stuff. She keeps the kids engaged and smiling all day. We appreciate Ms. Brown and all she has done during these uncertain times for her students. She is truly #DysartExtraordinary. üåü

post_text: When students return next week, meals will be served in closed containers. There will be no self-serve stations or beverage fountains. Students may also bring their own meals. Touchless checkout will be implemented and staff will take steps to speed up lunch lines and keep as much distance as possible between students. Schools have also developed procedures and schedules to help minimize the number of students in the cafeteria at one time. #DysartSafe Learn more at www.dysart.org/backtoschool

post_text: Students from the Valley Vista High School police and fire programs placed 100 flags on the lawn in front of the school in honor of first responders and the military on September 11. Valley Vista High School is the only school in Surprise that offers Law Enforcement and Fire Science Career and Technical Education programs to help train our future workforce in these fields. This year, Dysart is celebrating 100 years of serving the community. In celebration of the Dysart Centennial, 100 flags will be placed at various campuses throughout the year to acknowledge patriotic holidays and those who have served.

post_text: When students and staff arrive at school, face covers are required except while eating, or during recess or outdoor activities. Please note that our guidelines allow face masks, neck gaiters or face shields, as long as they fully cover both the mouth and nostrils. An exception may be made for students with medical conditions, those who have difficulty breathing or who are incapable of physically removing the face covering on his/her own. Learn more at http://ow.ly/25vp50BmxGw #DysartSafe

post_text: As students prepare to return to school on Sept. 14th & 21st, we are sharing some additional info and safety guidelines to remember. It is important for families to screen their children for symptoms each morning before sending them to school. Students must not come to school if any of the following symptoms are present: fever of 100.4 degrees or higher, or chills; and shortness of breath or difficulty breathing; muscle aches; sore throat; headache; fatigue; congestion or runny nose; cough; vomiting; diarrhea; or new loss of taste or smell.

Did you know? Our Summer Meal Service has been extended through December 31. All children 18 & under can receive free meals Monday-Friday at any Dysart school. Meals are available through drive-thru curbside pickup, or in the school cafeterias, for those attending Learning Labs or in-person classes. Parents may pick up the meals. Children do not need to be present, and children do not need to be enrolled in a Dysart school to participate.

For curbside meal service times, please visit dysart.org/meals. Menus and nutritional information can be found at dysart.nutrislice.com. Please note menus are subject to change based on demand and availability.

post_text:
The USDA has approved the extension of our Summer Meal Service through December 31 or until the Federal funding for this program is depleted. Beginning immediately, all children 18 & younger can receive free breakfast and lunch at any Dysart school. Breakfast and lunch meal service is available Monday-Friday through drive-thru curbside pickup, or in the school cafeterias, for those attending Learning Labs or in-person classes. Parents may pick up the meals. Children do not need to be present, and children do not need to be enrolled in a Dysart school to participate. A la carte items and snacks will be available for purchase in the cafeteria when in-person students return. SchoolCafe.com can be used to monitor purchases and make deposits to meal accounts for these items.

For curbside meal service times, please visit dysart.org/meals. Menus and nutritional information can be found at dysart.nutrislice.com. Please note menus are subject to change based on demand and availability.

post_text:
The Dysart Governing Board has called for a November 3, 2020 override continuation election. The proposed continuation of the 15% Maintenance and Operations (M&O) Override, which has been in place since 2000, will impact students by retaining highly qualified teachers and staff, provide academic support programs for Math and Reading, Maintain manageable class sizes, arts, physical education, and athletic programs, and fund all-day kindergarten.

In an effort to provide factual information so voters can make the best decision themselves and their families, we‚Äôve created a series of quiz questions to help you learn more about the details!

Remember to register to vote by October 5 at vote.org and Election Day is Tuesday, November 3, 2020.

In an effort to verify student information, Dysart parents and guardians are asked to complete the Annual Student Update/Acknowledgements available through the Parent Portal. We want to ensure that we can communicate with families regarding their student, or in the case of an emergency, so it is essential that we have accurate and up-to-date contact information.

Also, please note that in order to support both our in-person Remote Learning and online iSchool students, we have established Virtual Classroom Expectations to ensure a positive and productive learning experience for all participants. We ask that parents and students review them at your convenience at Dysart.org/StudentHandbook.

The Annual Student Update can be accessed by logging into the Parent Portal at dysart.org/ParentPortal, or through the Campus Parent mobile app, and clicking on the Annual Student Update link.

post_text: As Learning Labs kick off next week, we wanted to share some safety reminders for parents and students attending. There is a limit on the number of students allowed on campus. On Day 2 and each subsequent day, all drop-off and pick-up will be curbside only. Temperature checks will be required at drop off and two additional times during the day. Masks are required for all staff and students. Mask breaks are scheduled throughout the day and are not required while students are outside for break/recess. Frequent hand-washing and sanitizing will take place throughout the day. Students will be socially distanced in their own workstation in a large open space that may include the cafe, gymnasium, or media center. We are looking forward to providing Dysart students with a safe place to remain engaged in remote learning. As a reminder, Learning Labs are a requirement by the Governor's Executive Order 2020-51. Dysart continues to follow health benchmark data to determine when in-person classes can safely resume.

Are you new to Dysart or have a Kindergarten or 1st grader? Did you know all students are provided an email account to be able to access coursework and applications. A student‚Äôs username for Chromebooks and email is their Dysart email address. The basic format is the first initial of the student's first name, the student's last name, and the last 4 numbers of their student ID, followed by @dysartstudents.org.

Example: JAppleseed1234@dysartstudents.org

Parents can get their student‚Äôs ID number from the Parent Portal. If you are a new parent and do not have a Parent Portal account, please contact your school for the student‚Äôs ID number. Please contact your teacher to receive a default password.

post_text: 100 years ago today, Nathaniel M. Dysart, a local farmer, convened a three-person governing board and officially established Dysart Public Schools. What started as a one-room school house back in 1920 has grown into a community of 26 schools and more than 24,000 students. Dysart will be celebrating its Centennial throughout the 2020-2021 school year to honor our history, and we look forward to continuing that legacy for the next 100 years! #Dysart100

post_text:
In the Dysart Unified School District, all students will start school remotely on Tuesday, August 4 for the 2020-2021 school year. While Governor Ducey delayed the start of in-person classes statewide, starting remotely is still allowable. As a result, all Dysart PreK-12 classes will begin remotely on August 4, and families that select to attend an in-person option will transition to campus when it is allowable.

Dysart has already announced in-person and full-time online options for students, and continues to consider the feasibility of other models. The district expects to finalize class options and release specific details regarding each option and health and safety measures that will be implemented on July 6, 2020. Parents will be asked to select the option that best fits the needs of their student(s) and families by a specific date so that the district can appropriately plan for staffing needs.

post_text:
Valley Vista High School student athlete, Nick Mayberry, was recently awarded the Special Olympics Unified Sports Boys Athlete of the Year as part of the AZCentral Sports Awards.

Nick was nominated for the award by Valley Vista coach, Rebecca Milobar, for being an outstanding leader, role model, and team player. Nick has been a key member of the Valley Vista High School Unified Sports Team for the last three years, and is highly respected among his teachers and peers. Over the last three years, Nick has been a part of the 2018 Valley Vista State Champion Unified Basketball Team, the Gold Winning Valley Vista Unified Soccer Team, the Silver Award Winning Floorball Team, and much more.

The AZCentral Sports Awards seek to honor the best in local high school sports from the past year, while honoring them through an awards ceremony. This year, the ceremony was held virtually, featuring some of the biggest names in professional sports as award presenters. #WeAreDysart

post_text:
Elizabeth Moreno-Perla, Dysart Elementary School Kindergarten Teacher, was recently selected for the 2020-21 Maricopa County School Superintendent's Office Teacher Advisory Team (STAT). STAT consists of a diverse range of teachers representing 14 public school districts across Maricopa County. As a member of this team, Ms. Perla will meet quarterly with these fellow educators to provide valuable feedback, expertise, and insight into current issues and challenges. She will also have the opportunity to share ideas that will produce sufficient outcomes for students.

STAT is an initiative created by the office of the Maricopa County Superintendent Steve Watson, with the purpose of increasing teacher voice by including classroom practitioners in discussions around education practice and policy. Teacher representatives were chosen through an application and interview process and represent a diverse cross section of school settings, geographic locations, content specialties and experience levels. #WeAreDysart

post_text: Congrats to Matthew Klein and Troy Thomas from Valley Vista High School for earning 4th place in The Stock Market Game. This online simulation of the global capital markets engages students grades 4-12 in the world of economics, investing and personal finance. The team started with a "hypothetical" $100,000 and grew their portfolio to $127,325.62. The students analyzed real-time stock data, made decisions on how to buy and sell stocks for profit, and worked hard over the course of 12 weeks to complete the activity for their Economics class. Their team along with Keith Davis, Maria Ruiz, Anthony Rios and Jessica Rico de Leon made the top 10 out of 430 teams! Way to go and thanks Mr. Pinda for providing this opportunity to our students at Valley Vista! #WeAreDysart

post_text: The Dysart Unified School District Governing Board approved a change to the boundaries of Luke Elementary School and El Mirage Elementary School at the April 22, 2020 board meeting. The change goes into effect for the 2020-2021 school year. The district made the change in order to reduce transportation costs, maximize the use of all available facilities and to effectively position the district for incoming and projected growth. For more info, please visit dysart.org/Updates

post_text: A few weeks ago, the Dysart Unified School District asked schools to fire up their 3D printers to create surgical mask ear guards for local healthcare workers. To date, Dysart has made and distributed more than 2,500 surgical mask ear guards to more than 20 local hospitals, healthcare, and assisted living facilities in the area, including Banner Health, Mariposa Point Assisted Living of Surprise, and Arizona Kids Pediatrics. Dr. Kellis also challenged a few other local districts to make the ear guards as well. How are you doing Peoria Unified School District and Deer Valley Unified School District?

post_text: How thoughtful and kind! The Willow Canyon High School Key Club students have been working hard while at home to share some light, love, and cheer to those Grandmas and Grandpas who are unable to have visitors. The club chose a nursing home in Arkansas, Texas, and Illinois to spread cheer through the mail. Students created letters, drawings, and cards and have been mailing them out from their own homes. Check out a few of the letters and pictures the kids mailed. We hope they bring smiles and warm, fuzzy feelings to everyone during these trying times. #WeAreDysart

post_text:
The health, safety and well-being of our students, families and staff is our top priority. Dysart has plans in place for various actions that may be required in response to the Coronavirus and will take immediate action, as needed, to ensure the safety of our students and staff. Administration is preparing a communication to be released later this afternoon regarding our plans.

We are asking that students and staff stay home when they are sick and everyone should be practicing healthy habits. We are sanitizing our schools regularly as a precaution. Please remember that at this time there are no confirmed cases of Coronavirus in our district. For the most up to date information, please visit www.dysart.org

post_text:
The Surprise City Gov Public Works Department presented to Shadow Ridge High School Engineering students this past week. The presentation included information about the city‚Äôs Municipal Engineering Department, case studies, and tour of the Master Planned Community of Marley Park. The field trip concluded with a tour of the Water Management South Plant.

Kristin Tytler, Assistant Director and City Engineer for the City of Surprise and representatives from the engineering department shared the real world challenges they face while designing a master planned community, the structure of the Surprise Public Works and Water Resource Management and the coordination it takes between departments and staff when planning.

Students were then given real world scenarios posed by city engineers to take back to the classroom to solve and submit back as proposals for a practical application.

A big thanks to the city staff who provided this hands-on opportunity for our students! #DysartAcademics
